# Shared CLI + local secrets

When adding or changing skills in this repo:

## Do

- Keep CLI / Python code under `~/.ai-pro-skills/<skill>/` (this library).
- Register with **`cp` of `SKILL.md` only** (not full tree), unless the skill is an
  explicit full-tree exception (`google-workspace`, `powerpoint`).
- Put credentials in **`$DEST/<skill>/.env`** (project: `./.cursor/skills/<skill>/.env`,
  global: `~/.cursor/skills/<skill>/.env`) — one account per workspace.
- Resolve paths with [`common/skill_home.py`](common/skill_home.py):

```python
from pathlib import Path
import sys
_LIB = Path(__file__).resolve().parent
sys.path.insert(0, str(_LIB.parent))
from common.skill_home import SkillHome

_home = SkillHome("my-skill", library_home=_LIB)
env = _home.env_path()           # per-workspace .env
lib = _home.get_library_home()   # shared CLI dir
```

- Expose a thin `<skill>/_skill_home.py` wrapper so local imports stay stable.
- Document working dir as `~/.ai-pro-skills/<skill>` and the `.env` table in `SKILL.md`.
- Ship `.env.example` + gitignore `.env`; never commit secrets.

## Don't

- Don't store the real `.env` / tokens only under `~/.ai-pro-skills/<skill>/` for skills
  that should support multiple workspaces.
- Don't `cp -R` the whole skill into Cursor/Hermes for new Python CLIs (shared model).
- Don't invent a second path helper — extend `common/skill_home.py` instead.
- Don't hardcode `~/.reddit-credentials` or similar home-dotfiles.

## Install reminder

```bash
mkdir -p "$DEST/my-skill"
cp ~/.ai-pro-skills/my-skill/SKILL.md "$DEST/my-skill/SKILL.md"
cp ~/.ai-pro-skills/my-skill/.env.example "$DEST/my-skill/.env"
cd ~/.ai-pro-skills/my-skill && ~/.ai-pro-skills/.venv/bin/python cli.py …
```
